<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Glyceria </i>x<i>occidentalis </i>is a perennial grass that forms very loose clumps with stems rooting at the nodes. Its underground stems and floating leaves exhibit rapid growth, which aids in reducing erosion along the edges of streams and lakes. <i>G. </i>x<i>occidentalis </i>has been used for restoration of freshwater marshes, vernal pools, and depressions within wetland prairies (Darris 2006). It appears to be a hybrid of <i>Glyceria leptostachya</i> and <i>Glyceria fluitans</i> based on DNA studies, and the latter taxon is an introduced non-native to California (USDA-NRCS 2014).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Glyceria </i>x<i>occidentalis </i>occurs commonly and widely in the Pacific Northwest at low elevations, especially along streams and in wet meadow depressions (Darris 2006); however, we have minimal information regarding the existence as an alliance. S. Smith (1998) described a <i>G. </i>x<i>occidentalis </i>meadow/marsh type on the Modoc National Forest. These stands appear ecologically similar to stands of the <i>Eleocharis macrostachya </i>alliance. Stands also appear ecologically similar to associations containing <i>G. borealis, G. elata, G. grandis, </i>and <i>G. striata </i>from shallow waters, mudflats, and stream banks in Oregon (Christy 2004, Kagan et al. 2004). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The range of <i>Glyceria </i>x<i>occidentalis</i> includes Great Valley (262A), Klamath Mountains (M261A), Northern California Coast (263A), Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B), Northern California Interior Coast Ranges (M261C), and Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F). S. Smith (1998b) sampled three stands dominated by <i>G. </i>x<i>occidentalis</i> in the lower montane elevations of the Southern Cascades (M261D). We need more sampling and analysis of seasonally flooded and ephemeral wetland vegetation of this and similar alliances in the state to evaluate their relationships. </div>
</div>

	

    
